00:05:10.460 --> 00:05:11.760
&gt;&gt; Don Winslow: You know what?

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:13.240
I call it the chair factor.

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:15.700
First of all, I've been
around cops my whole life.

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:17.770
My godfather was a cop.

00:05:17.770 --> 00:05:20.580
I worked in New York City as a P.I.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:22.030
in Times Square.

00:05:22.030 --> 00:05:25.940
So I dealt with cops a lot
so I've worked with cops.

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:30.220
I've worked cases against
cops in Los Angeles.

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:33.670
So I've been around them
my whole adult life.

00:05:33.670 --> 00:05:36.990
But specifically for this book,
it was a matter not so much

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:39.400
of having interviews
but becoming the chair.

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:42.500
Do you know how when you buy
a new chair or a new sofa?

00:05:42.500 --> 00:05:46.050 position:56%
For the first couple of weeks you go
in the room, and that's all you see.

00:05:46.050 --> 00:05:47.350
It's a chair.

00:05:47.350 --> 00:05:48.650
It's the sofa.

00:05:48.650 --> 00:05:50.450
It's new. It's there,
dominates the room.

00:05:50.450 --> 00:05:55.800
A couple of weeks later,
it's the chair.

00:05:55.800 --> 00:05:58.380
And so I think for
researching any book

00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:02.020
like this is largely a
matter of becoming the chair.

00:06:02.020 --> 00:06:04.080
Just to be there.

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:06.880
And it's like any relationship.

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:13.770
It takes time and to sit and to
listen and to hear what they say

00:06:13.770 --> 00:06:17.600
and to ask fewer and
fewer questions really.

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:19.140
&gt;&gt; Maureen Corrigan:
Did you ride along?

00:06:19.140 --> 00:06:20.690
Did you -- yeah, yeah.

00:06:20.690 --> 00:06:21.990
&gt;&gt; Don Winslow: Sorry,
